## Initial repo setup:

```
git init --bare $HOME/.gentoo-configs
alias dgit='git --git-dir=$HOME/.gentoo-configs/ --work-tree=$HOME'
dgit config status.showUntrackedFiles no
```

## Usage

Now any files in $HOME can be versioned as usual with things like:
```
dgit status
dgit add .vimrc
dgit commit -m 'add vimrc'
dgit push
```

To see what files are being tracked:
`dgit ls-tree --full-tree -r HEAD`
or simply `dgit ls-files`


## Install the dotfiles onto a new system

```
curl -fsSL https://proton.me/download/pass-cli/install.sh | bash

git clone --bare git@github.com:grahamlopez/gentoo-configs $HOME/.gentoo-configs
dgit checkout

utils/fix_file_perms.sh
```

If there are already dotfiles present, then need to back them up and move out of
the way and rerun `dgit checkout` (use the bootstrap script)


## git configuration

Sometimes, I have had to manually configure the repo after checkout;
edit `.gentoo-configs/config` and add the following:

```
[remote "origin"]
        url = git@github.com:grahamlopez/gentoo-configs.git
        fetch = +refs/heads/*:refs/remotes/origin/*
[status]
        showUntrackedFiles = no

```

To change the remote e.g. from https: to git:
```
git remote set-url origin git@github.com/grahamlopez/gentoo-configs.git
```
